P_HTM[1634]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, iminā vihārena viharato viññāṇañcāyatanasahagatā saññāmanasikārā samudācaranti. Svassa me hoti ābādho.**While I was in that meditation, perceptions and attentions accompanied by the dimension of infinite consciousness beset me, and that was an affliction for me.*";
P_HTM[1635]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, sukhino dukkhaṃ uppajjeyya yāvadeva ābādhāya;**Suppose a happy person were to experience pain; that would be an affliction for them.*";
P_HTM[1636]="*evamevassa me viññāṇañcāyatanasahagatā saññāmanasikārā samudācaranti. Svassa me hoti ābādho.**In the same way, when perceptions and attentions accompanied by the dimension of infinite consciousness beset me, that was an affliction for me.*";
P_HTM[1637]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, etadahosi:**Then I thought,*";
P_HTM[1638]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja vihareyyan’ti.**‘Why don’t I, going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, enter and remain in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception?’*";
P_HTM[1639]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, nevasaññānāsaññāyatane cittaṃ na pakkhandati nappasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati etaṃ santanti passato.**But my mind wasn’t eager for the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception; it wasn’t confident, settled, and decided about it. I didn’t see it as peaceful.*";
P_HTM[1640]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, etadahosi:**Then I thought,*";
P_HTM[1641]="*‘ko nu kho hetu ko paccayo, yena me nevasaññānāsaññāyatane cittaṃ na pakkhandati nappasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati etaṃ santanti passato’?**‘What is the cause, what is the reason why my mind isn’t eager for the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, and not confident, settled, and decided about it? Why don’t I see it as peaceful?’*";
P_HTM[1642]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, etadahosi:**Then I thought,*";
P_HTM[1643]="*‘ākiñcaññāyatane kho me ādīnavo adiṭṭho, so ca me abahulīkato, nevasaññānāsaññāyatane ca ānisaṃso anadhigato, so ca me anāsevito.**‘I haven’t seen the drawbacks of the dimension of nothingness, and so I haven’t cultivated that. I haven’t realized the benefits of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, and so I haven’t developed that.*";
P_HTM[1644]="*Tasmā me nevasaññānāsaññāyatane cittaṃ na pakkhandati nappasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati etaṃ santanti passato’.**That’s why my mind isn’t eager for the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, and not confident, settled, and decided about it. And it’s why I don’t see it as peaceful.’*";
P_HTM[1645]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, etadahosi:**Then I thought,*";
P_HTM[1646]="*‘sace kho ahaṃ ākiñcaññāyatane ādīnavaṃ disvā taṃ bahulaṃ kareyyaṃ, nevasaññānāsaññāyatane ānisaṃsaṃ adhigamma tamāseveyyaṃ, ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ vijjati yaṃ me nevasaññānāsaññāyatane cittaṃ pakkhandeyya pasīdeyya santiṭṭheyya vimucceyya etaṃ santanti passato’.**‘Suppose that, seeing the drawbacks of the dimension of nothingness, I were to cultivate that. And suppose that, realizing the benefits of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, I were to develop that. It’s possible that my mind would be eager for the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception; it would be confident, settled, and decided about it. And I would see it as peaceful.’*";
P_HTM[1647]="*So kho ahaṃ, ānanda, aparena samayena ākiñcaññāyatane ādīnavaṃ disvā taṃ bahulamakāsiṃ, nevasaññānāsaññāyatane ānisaṃsaṃ adhigamma tamāseviṃ.**And so, after some time, I saw the drawbacks of the dimension of nothingness and cultivated that, and I realized the benefits of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception and developed that.*";
P_HTM[1648]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, nevasaññānāsaññāyatane cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati etaṃ santanti passato.**Then my mind was eager for the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception; it was confident, settled, and decided about it. I saw it as peaceful.*";
P_HTM[1649]="*So kho ahaṃ, ānanda, sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And so, going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, I was entering and remaining in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[1650]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, iminā vihārena viharato ākiñcaññāyatanasahagatā saññāmanasikārā samudācaranti. Svassa me hoti ābādho.**While I was in that meditation, perceptions and attentions accompanied by the dimension of nothingness beset me, and that was an affliction for me.*";
P_HTM[1651]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, sukhino dukkhaṃ uppajjeyya yāvadeva ābādhāya;**Suppose a happy person were to experience pain; that would be an affliction for them.*";
P_HTM[1652]="*evamevassa me ākiñcaññāyatanasahagatā saññāmanasikārā samudācaranti. Svassa me hoti ābādho.**In the same way, when perceptions and attentions accompanied by the dimension of nothingness beset me, that was an affliction for me.*";
P_HTM[1653]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, etadahosi:**Then I thought,*";
P_HTM[1654]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja vihareyyan’ti.**‘Why don’t I, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, enter and remain in the cessation of perception and feeling?’*";
P_HTM[1655]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, saññāvedayitanirodhe cittaṃ na pakkhandati nappasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati etaṃ santanti passato.**But my mind wasn’t eager for the cessation of perception and feeling; it wasn’t confident, settled, and decided about it. I didn’t see it as peaceful.*";
P_HTM[1656]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, etadahosi:**Then I thought,*";
P_HTM[1657]="*‘ko nu kho hetu, ko paccayo, yena me saññāvedayitanirodhe cittaṃ na pakkhandati nappasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati etaṃ santanti passato’?**‘What is the cause, what is the reason why my mind isn’t eager for the cessation of perception and feeling, and not confident, settled, and decided about it? Why don’t I see it as peaceful?’*";
P_HTM[1658]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, etadahosi:**Then I thought,*";
P_HTM[1659]="*‘nevasaññānāsaññāyatane kho me ādīnavo adiṭṭho, so ca me abahulīkato, saññāvedayitanirodhe ca ānisaṃso anadhigato, so ca me anāsevito.**‘I haven’t seen the drawbacks of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, and so I haven’t cultivated that. I haven’t realized the benefits of the cessation of perception and feeling, and so I haven’t developed that.*";
P_HTM[1660]="*Tasmā me saññāvedayitanirodhe cittaṃ na pakkhandati nappasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati etaṃ santanti passato’.**That’s why my mind isn’t eager for the cessation of perception and feeling, and not confident, settled, and decided about it. And it’s why I don’t see it as peaceful.’*";
P_HTM[1661]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, etadahosi:**Then I thought,*";
P_HTM[1662]="*‘sace kho ahaṃ nevasaññānāsaññāyatane ādīnavaṃ disvā taṃ bahulaṃ kareyyaṃ, saññāvedayitanirodhe ānisaṃsaṃ adhigamma tamāseveyyaṃ, ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ vijjati yaṃ me saññāvedayitanirodhe cittaṃ pakkhandeyya pasīdeyya santiṭṭheyya vimucceyya etaṃ santanti passato’.**‘Suppose that, seeing the drawbacks of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, I were to cultivate that. And suppose that, realizing the benefits of the cessation of perception and feeling, I were to develop that. It’s possible that my mind would be eager for cessation of perception and feeling; it would be confident, settled, and decided about it. And I would see it as peaceful.’*";
P_HTM[1663]="*So kho ahaṃ, ānanda, aparena samayena nevasaññānāsaññāyatane ādīnavaṃ disvā taṃ bahulamakāsiṃ, saññāvedayitanirodhe ānisaṃsaṃ adhigamma tamāseviṃ.**And so, after some time, I saw the drawbacks of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception and cultivated that, and I realized the benefits of the cessation of perception and feeling and developed that.*";
P_HTM[1664]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, ānanda, saññāvedayitanirodhe cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati etaṃ santanti passato.**Then my mind was eager for the cessation of perception and feeling; it was confident, settled, and decided about it. I saw it as peaceful.*";
P_HTM[1665]="*So kho ahaṃ, ānanda, sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharāmi, paññāya ca me disvā āsavā parikkhayaṃ agamaṃsu.**And so, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, I was entering and remaining in the cessation of perception and feeling. And, having seen with wisdom, my defilements were ended.*";
P_HTM[1666]="*Yāvakīvañcāhaṃ, ānanda, imā nava anupubbavihārasamāpattiyo na evaṃ anulomapaṭilomaṃ samāpajjimpi vuṭṭhahimpi, neva tāvāhaṃ, ānanda, sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya ‘anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho’ti paccaññāsiṃ.**As long as I hadn’t entered into and withdrawn from these nine progressive meditative attainments in both forward and reverse order, I didn’t announce my supreme perfect awakening in this world with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[1667]="*Yato ca kho ahaṃ, ānanda, imā nava anupubbavihārasamāpattiyo evaṃ anulomapaṭilomaṃ samāpajjimpi vuṭṭhahimpi, athāhaṃ, ānanda, sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya ‘anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho’ti paccaññāsiṃ.**But when I had entered into and withdrawn from these nine progressive meditative attainments in both forward and reverse order, I announced my supreme perfect awakening in this world with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[1668]="*Ñāṇañca pana me dassanaṃ udapādi:**Knowledge and vision arose in me:*";
P_HTM[1669]="*‘akuppā me cetovimutti, ayamantimā jāti, natthi dāni punabbhavo’”ti.**‘My freedom is unshakable; this is my last rebirth; now there are no more future lives.’”*";
P_HTM[1670]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1671]="*Mahāvaggo catuttho.* **";
P_HTM[1672]="*Dve vihārā ca nibbānaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1673]="*gāvī jhānena pañcamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[1674]="*Ānando brāhmaṇā devo,* **";
P_HTM[1675]="*nāgena tapussena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[1676]="*1(10) 5. Rāgapeyyālaṃ**Similarity*";
P_HTM[1677]="*1. Sambādhasuttaṃ**Cramped*";
P_HTM[1678]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ānando kosambiyaṃ viharati ghositārāme.**At one time Venerable Ānanda was staying near Kosambi, in Ghosita’s Monastery.*";
P_HTM[1679]="*Atha kho āyasmā udāyī yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā ānandena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then Venerable Udāyī went up to Venerable Ānanda and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[1680]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā udāyī āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1681]="*“vuttamidaṃ, āvuso, pañcālacaṇḍena devaputtena:**“Reverend, this was said by the god Pañcālacaṇḍa:*";
P_HTM[1682]="*‘Sambādhe gataṃ okāsaṃ,**‘The opening amid confinement*";
P_HTM[1683]="*Avidvā bhūrimedhaso;**was discovered by the Buddha of vast intelligence,*";
P_HTM[1684]="*Yo jhānamabujjhi buddho,**who woke up to absorption,*";
P_HTM[1685]="*Paṭilīnanisabho munī’ti.**the sage, the solitary bull.’*";
P_HTM[1686]="*Katamo, āvuso, sambādho, katamo sambādhe okāsādhigamo vutto bhagavatā”ti?**But what is confinement, and what is the opening amid confinement that the Buddha spoke of?”*";
P_HTM[1687]="*“Pañcime, āvuso, kāmaguṇā sambādho vutto bhagavatā.**“Reverend, these five kinds of sensual stimulation are called ‘confinement’ by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1688]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1689]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā,**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1690]="*sotaviññeyyā saddā … pe …**Sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[1691]="*ghānaviññeyyā gandhā …**Smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[1692]="*jivhāviññeyyā rasā …**Tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[1693]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1694]="*Ime kho, āvuso, pañca kāmaguṇā sambādho vutto bhagavatā.**These are the five kinds of sensual stimulation that are called ‘confinement’ by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1695]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Now, take a mendicant who, quite secluded from sensual pleasures … enters and remains in the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[1696]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, sambādhe okāsādhigamo vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of creating an opening amid confinement in a qualified sense.*";
P_HTM[1697]="*Tatrāpatthi sambādho.**But it is still confined.*";
P_HTM[1698]="*Kiñca tattha sambādho?**Confined by what?*";
P_HTM[1699]="*Yadeva tattha vitakkavicārā aniruddhā honti, ayamettha sambādho.**Whatever placing of the mind and keeping it connected has not ceased is the confinement there.*";
P_HTM[1700]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā … pe … dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled … enters and remains in the second absorption.*";
P_HTM[1701]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, sambādhe okāsādhigamo vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of creating an opening amid confinement in a qualified sense.*";
P_HTM[1702]="*Tatrāpatthi sambādho.**But it is still confined.*";
P_HTM[1703]="*Kiñca tattha sambādho?**Confined by what?*";
P_HTM[1704]="*Yadeva tattha pīti aniruddhā hoti, ayamettha sambādho.**Whatever rapture has not ceased is the confinement there.*";
P_HTM[1705]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā … pe … tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, with the fading away of rapture … enters and remains in the third absorption.*";
P_HTM[1706]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, sambādhe okāsādhigamo vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of creating an opening amid confinement in a qualified sense.*";
P_HTM[1707]="*Tatrāpatthi sambādho.**But it is still confined.*";
P_HTM[1708]="*Kiñca tattha sambādho?**Confined by what?*";
P_HTM[1709]="*Yadeva tattha upekkhāsukhaṃ aniruddhaṃ hoti, ayamettha sambādho.**Whatever equanimous bliss has not ceased is the confinement there.*";
P_HTM[1710]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā … pe … catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, giving up pleasure and pain … enters and remains in the fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[1711]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, sambādhe okāsādhigamo vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of creating an opening amid confinement in a qualified sense.*";
P_HTM[1712]="*Tatrāpatthi sambādho.**But it is still confined.*";
P_HTM[1713]="*Kiñca tattha sambādho?**Confined by what?*";
P_HTM[1714]="*Yadeva tattha rūpasaññā aniruddhā hoti, ayamettha sambādho.**Whatever perception of form has not ceased is the confinement there.*";
P_HTM[1715]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, enters and remains in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[1716]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, sambādhe okāsādhigamo vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of creating an opening amid confinement in a qualified sense.*";
P_HTM[1717]="*Tatrāpatthi sambādho.**But it is still confined.*";
P_HTM[1718]="*Kiñca tattha sambādho?**Confined by what?*";
P_HTM[1719]="*Yadeva tattha ākāsānañcāyatanasaññā aniruddhā hoti, ayamettha sambādho.**Whatever perception of the dimension of infinite space has not ceased is the confinement there.*";
P_HTM[1720]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, a mendicant, going totally beyond the dimension of infinite space, aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, enters and remains in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1721]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, sambādhe okāsādhigamo vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of creating an opening amid confinement in a qualified sense.*";
P_HTM[1722]="*Tatrāpatthi sambādho.**But it is still confined.*";
P_HTM[1723]="*Kiñca tattha sambādho?**Confined by what?*";
P_HTM[1724]="*Yadeva tattha viññāṇañcāyatanasaññā aniruddhā hoti, ayamettha sambādho.**Whatever perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness has not ceased is the confinement there.*";
P_HTM[1725]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, a mendicant, going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, enters and remains in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[1726]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, sambādhe okāsādhigamo vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of creating an opening amid confinement in a qualified sense.*";
P_HTM[1727]="*Tatrāpatthi sambādho.**But it is still confined.*";
P_HTM[1728]="*Kiñca tattha sambādho?**Confined by what?*";
P_HTM[1729]="*Yadeva tattha ākiñcaññāyatanasaññā aniruddhā hoti, ayamettha sambādho.**Whatever perception of the dimension of nothingness has not ceased is the confinement there.*";
P_HTM[1730]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, enters and remains in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[1731]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, sambādhe okāsādhigamo vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of creating an opening amid confinement in a qualified sense.*";
P_HTM[1732]="*Tatrāpatthi sambādho.**But it is still confined.*";
P_HTM[1733]="*Kiñca tattha sambādho?**Confined by what?*";
P_HTM[1734]="*Yadeva tattha nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasaññā aniruddhā hoti, ayamettha sambādho.**Whatever perception of neither perception nor non-perception has not ceased is the confinement there.*";
P_HTM[1735]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati, paññāya cassa disvā āsavā parikkhīṇā honti.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, enters and remains in the cessation of perception and feeling. And, having seen with wisdom, their defilements come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1736]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, sambādhe okāsādhigamo vutto bhagavatā nippariyāyenā”ti.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of creating an opening amid confinement in a definitive sense.”*";
P_HTM[1737]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1738]="*2. Kāyasakkhīsuttaṃ**A Personal Witness*";
P_HTM[1739]="*“‘Kāyasakkhī, kāyasakkhī’ti, āvuso, vuccati.**“Reverend, they speak of a person called ‘personal witness’.*";
P_HTM[1740]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, kāyasakkhī vutto bhagavatā”ti?**What is the personal witness that the Buddha spoke of?”*";
P_HTM[1741]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**“First, take a mendicant who, quite secluded from sensual pleasures … enters and remains in the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[1742]="*Yathā yathā ca tadāyatanaṃ tathā tathā naṃ kāyena phusitvā viharati.**They meditate directly experiencing that dimension in every way.*";
P_HTM[1743]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, kāyasakkhī vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena. (1)**To this extent the Buddha spoke of the personal witness in a qualified sense.*";
P_HTM[1744]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā … pe … dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, enters and remains in the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[1745]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[1746]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[1747]="*Yathā yathā ca tadāyatanaṃ tathā tathā naṃ kāyena phusitvā viharati.**They meditate directly experiencing that dimension in every way.*";
P_HTM[1748]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, kāyasakkhī vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena. (2–4.)**To this extent the Buddha spoke of the personal witness in a qualified sense.*";
P_HTM[1749]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, enters and remains in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[1750]="*Yathā yathā ca tadāyatanaṃ tathā tathā naṃ kāyena phusitvā viharati.**They meditate directly experiencing that dimension in every way.*";
P_HTM[1751]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, kāyasakkhī vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena … pe …. (5–8.)**To this extent the Buddha spoke of the personal witness in a qualified sense. Furthermore, take a mendicant who enters and remains in the dimension of infinite consciousness … the dimension of nothingness … the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception …*";
P_HTM[1752]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati, paññāya cassa disvā āsavā parikkhīṇā honti.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, enters and remains in the cessation of perception and feeling. And, having seen with wisdom, their defilements come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1753]="*Yathā yathā ca tadāyatanaṃ tathā tathā naṃ kāyena phusitvā viharati.**They meditate directly experiencing that dimension in every way.*";
P_HTM[1754]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, kāyasakkhī vutto bhagavatā nippariyāyenā”ti. (9)**To this extent the Buddha spoke of the personal witness in a definitive sense.”*";
P_HTM[1755]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1756]="*3. Paññāvimuttasuttaṃ**Freed by Wisdom*";
P_HTM[1757]="*“‘Paññāvimutto, paññāvimutto’ti, āvuso, vuccati.**“Reverend, they speak of a person called ‘freed by wisdom’.*";
P_HTM[1758]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, paññāvimutto vutto bhagavatā”ti?**What is the one freed by wisdom that the Buddha spoke of?”*";
P_HTM[1759]="*“Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati,**“First, take a mendicant who, quite secluded from sensual pleasures … enters and remains in the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[1760]="*paññāya ca naṃ pajānāti.**And they understand that with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1761]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, paññāvimutto vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena … pe ….**To this extent the Buddha spoke of the one freed by wisdom in a qualified sense. …*";
P_HTM[1762]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati, paññāya cassa disvā āsavā parikkhīṇā honti,**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, enters and remains in the cessation of perception and feeling. And, having seen with wisdom, their defilements come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1763]="*paññāya ca naṃ pajānāti.**And they understand that with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1764]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, paññāvimutto vutto bhagavatā nippariyāyenā”ti.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of the one freed by wisdom in a definitive sense.”*";
P_HTM[1765]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1766]="*4. Ubhatobhāgavimuttasuttaṃ**Freed Both Ways*";
P_HTM[1767]="*“‘Ubhatobhāgavimutto, ubhatobhāgavimutto’ti, āvuso, vuccati.**“Reverend, they speak of a person called ‘freed both ways’.*";
P_HTM[1768]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, ubhatobhāgavimutto vutto bhagavatā”ti?**What is the one freed both ways that the Buddha spoke of?”*";
P_HTM[1769]="*“Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**“First, take a mendicant who, quite secluded from sensual pleasures … enters and remains in the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[1770]="*Yathā yathā ca tadāyatanaṃ tathā tathā naṃ kāyena phusitvā viharati, paññāya ca naṃ pajānāti.**They meditate directly experiencing that dimension in every way. And they understand that with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1771]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, ubhatobhāgavimutto vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena … pe ….**To this extent the Buddha spoke of the one freed both ways in a qualified sense. …*";
P_HTM[1772]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati, paññāya cassa disvā āsavā parikkhīṇā honti.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, enters and remains in the cessation of perception and feeling. And, having seen with wisdom, their defilements come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1773]="*Yathā yathā ca tadāyatanaṃ tathā tathā naṃ kāyena phusitvā viharati, paññāya ca naṃ pajānāti.**They meditate directly experiencing that dimension in every way. And they understand that with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1774]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, ubhatobhāgavimutto vutto bhagavatā nippariyāyenā”ti.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of the one freed both ways in a definitive sense.”*";
P_HTM[1775]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1776]="*5. Sandiṭṭhikadhammasuttaṃ**In This Very Life*";
P_HTM[1777]="*“‘Sandiṭṭhiko dhammo, sandiṭṭhiko dhammo’ti, āvuso, vuccati.**“Reverend, they speak of ‘a teaching visible in this very life’.*";
P_HTM[1778]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, sandiṭṭhiko dhammo vutto bhagavatā”ti?**In what way did the Buddha speak of a teaching visible in this very life?”*";
P_HTM[1779]="*“Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**“First, take a mendicant who, quite secluded from sensual pleasures … enters and remains in the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[1780]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, sandiṭṭhiko dhammo vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena … pe ….**To this extent the Buddha spoke of the teaching visible in this very life in a qualified sense. …*";
P_HTM[1781]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati, paññāya cassa disvā āsavā parikkhīṇā honti.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, enters and remains in the cessation of perception and feeling. And, having seen with wisdom, their defilements come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1782]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, sandiṭṭhiko dhammo vutto bhagavatā nippariyāyenā”ti.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of the teaching visible in this very life in a definitive sense.”*";
P_HTM[1783]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1784]="*6. Sandiṭṭhikanibbānasuttaṃ**Extinguishment Is Visible in This Very Life*";
P_HTM[1785]="*“‘Sandiṭṭhikaṃ nibbānaṃ, sandiṭṭhikaṃ nibbānan’ti, āvuso, vuccati.**“Reverend, they say that ‘extinguishment is visible in this very life’.*";
P_HTM[1786]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, sandiṭṭhikaṃ nibbānaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā”ti?**In what way did the Buddha say extinguishment is visible in this very life?”*";
P_HTM[1787]="*“Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**“First, take a mendicant who, quite secluded from sensual pleasures … enters and remains in the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[1788]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, sandiṭṭhikaṃ nibbānaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā pariyāyena … pe ….**To this extent the Buddha said that extinguishment is visible in this very life in a qualified sense. …*";
P_HTM[1789]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati, paññāya cassa disvā āsavā parikkhīṇā honti.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, enters and remains in the cessation of perception and feeling. And, having seen with wisdom, their defilements come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1790]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, sandiṭṭhikaṃ nibbānaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā nippariyāyenā”ti.**To this extent the Buddha said that extinguishment is visible in this very life in a definitive sense.”*";
P_HTM[1791]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1792]="*7. Nibbānasuttaṃ**Extinguishment*";
P_HTM[1793]="*“‘Nibbānaṃ, nibbānan’ti, āvuso, vuccati … pe ….**“Reverend, they speak of ‘extinguishment’. …”*";
P_HTM[1794]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1795]="*8. Parinibbānasuttaṃ**Final Extinguishment*";
P_HTM[1796]="*“‘Parinibbānaṃ, parinibbānan’ti … pe ….**“Reverend, they speak of ‘final extinguishment’. …”*";
P_HTM[1797]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1798]="*9. Tadaṅganibbānasuttaṃ**Extinguishment in a Certain Respect*";
P_HTM[1799]="*“‘Tadaṅganibbānaṃ, tadaṅganibbānan’ti, āvuso, vuccati … pe ….**“Reverend, they speak of ‘extinguishment in a certain respect’. …”*";
P_HTM[1800]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1801]="*10. Diṭṭhadhammanibbānasuttaṃ**Extinguishment in the Present Life*";
P_HTM[1802]="*“‘Diṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ diṭṭhadhammanibbānan’ti, āvuso, vuccati.**“Reverend, they speak of ‘extinguishment in the present life’.*";
P_HTM[1803]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, diṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā”ti?**In what way did the Buddha speak of extinguishment in the present life?”*";
P_HTM[1804]="*“Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**“First, take a mendicant who, quite secluded from sensual pleasures … enters and remains in the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[1805]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, diṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā pariyāyena … pe ….**To this extent the Buddha spoke of extinguishment in the present life in a qualified sense. …*";
P_HTM[1806]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati, paññāya cassa disvā āsavā parikkhīṇā honti.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, enters and remains in the cessation of perception and feeling. And, having seen with wisdom, their defilements come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1807]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, diṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā nippariyāyenā”ti.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of extinguishment in the present life in a definitive sense.”*";
P_HTM[1808]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1809]="*Sāmaññavaggo pañcamo.* **";
P_HTM[1810]="*Sambādho kāyasakkhī paññā,* **";
P_HTM[1811]="*Ubhatobhāgo sandiṭṭhikā dve;* **";
P_HTM[1812]="*Nibbānaṃ parinibbānaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1813]="*Tadaṅgadiṭṭhadhammikena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[1814]="*Paṭhamo paṇṇāsako samatto.* **";
P_HTM[1815]="*1(10) 5. Rāgapeyyālaṃ**A Safe Place*";
P_HTM[1816]="*1. Khemasuttaṃ**A Safe Place*";
P_HTM[1817]="*“‘Khemaṃ, kheman’ti, āvuso, vuccati.**“Reverend, they speak of ‘a safe place’.*";
P_HTM[1818]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, khemaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā”ti?**In what way did the Buddha speak of a safe place?”*";
P_HTM[1819]="*“Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**“First, take a mendicant who, quite secluded from sensual pleasures … enters and remains in the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[1820]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, khemaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā pariyāyena … pe ….**To this extent the Buddha spoke of a safe place in a qualified sense. …*";
P_HTM[1821]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati, paññāya cassa disvā āsavā parikkhīṇā honti.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, enters and remains in the cessation of perception and feeling. And, having seen with wisdom, their defilements come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1822]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, khemaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā nippariyāyenā”ti.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of a safe place in a definitive sense.”*";
P_HTM[1823]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1824]="*2. Khemappattasuttaṃ**Reaching a Safe Place*";
P_HTM[1825]="*“‘Khemappatto, khemappatto’ti, āvuso, vuccati ….**“Reverend, they speak of ‘reaching a safe place’. …”*";
P_HTM[1826]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1827]="*3. Amatasuttaṃ**The Deathless*";
P_HTM[1828]="*“‘Amataṃ, amatan’ti, āvuso, vuccati ….**“Reverend, they speak of ‘the deathless’. …”*";
P_HTM[1829]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1830]="*4. Amatappattasuttaṃ**Reaching the Deathless*";
P_HTM[1831]="*“‘Amatappatto, amatappatto’ti, āvuso, vuccati ….**“Reverend, they speak of ‘reaching the deathless’. …”*";
P_HTM[1832]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1833]="*5. Abhayasuttaṃ**A Place Without Fear*";
P_HTM[1834]="*“‘Abhayaṃ, abhayan’ti, āvuso, vuccati ….**“Reverend, they speak of ‘a place without fear’. …”*";
P_HTM[1835]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1836]="*6. Abhayappattasuttaṃ**Reaching a Place Without Fear*";
P_HTM[1837]="*“‘Abhayappatto, abhayappatto’ti, āvuso, vuccati ….**“Reverend, they speak of ‘reaching a place without fear’. …”*";
P_HTM[1838]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1839]="*7. Passaddhisuttaṃ**Tranquility*";
P_HTM[1840]="*“‘Passaddhi, passaddhī’ti, āvuso, vuccati ….**“Reverend, they speak of ‘tranquility’. …”*";
P_HTM[1841]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1842]="*8. Anupubbapassaddhisuttaṃ**Progressive Tranquility*";
P_HTM[1843]="*“‘Anupubbapassaddhi, anupubbapassaddhī’ti, āvuso, vuccati ….**“Reverend, they speak of ‘progressive tranquility’. …”*";
P_HTM[1844]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1845]="*9. Nirodhasuttaṃ**Cessation*";
P_HTM[1846]="*“‘Nirodho, nirodho’ti, āvuso, vuccati ….**“Reverend, they speak of ‘cessation’. …”*";
P_HTM[1847]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1848]="*10. Anupubbanirodhasuttaṃ**Progressive Cessation*";
P_HTM[1849]="*“‘Anupubbanirodho, anupubbanirodho’ti, āvuso, vuccati.**“Reverend, they speak of ‘progressive cessation’.*";
P_HTM[1850]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, anupubbanirodho vutto bhagavatā”ti?**What is the progressive cessation that the Buddha spoke of?”*";
P_HTM[1851]="*“Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**“First, take a mendicant who, quite secluded from sensual pleasures … enters and remains in the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[1852]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, anupubbanirodho vutto bhagavatā pariyāyena … pe ….**To this extent the Buddha spoke of progressive cessation in a qualified sense. …*";
P_HTM[1853]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati, paññāya cassa disvā āsavā parikkhīṇā honti.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, enters and remains in the cessation of perception and feeling. And, having seen with wisdom, their defilements come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1854]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, āvuso, anupubbanirodho vutto bhagavatā nippariyāyenā”ti.**To this extent the Buddha spoke of progressive cessation in a definitive sense.”*";
P_HTM[1855]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1856]="*11. Abhabbasuttaṃ**Requirements for Perfection*";
P_HTM[1857]="*“Nava, bhikkhave, dhamme appahāya abhabbo arahattaṃ sacchikātuṃ.**“Mendicants, without giving up nine things you can’t realize perfection.*";
P_HTM[1858]="*Katame nava?**What nine?*";
P_HTM[1859]="*Rāgaṃ, dosaṃ, mohaṃ, kodhaṃ, upanāhaṃ, makkhaṃ, paḷāsaṃ, issaṃ, macchariyaṃ—**Greed, hate, delusion, anger, hostility, offensiveness, contempt, jealousy, and stinginess.*";
P_HTM[1860]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, nava dhamme appahāya abhabbo arahattaṃ sacchikātuṃ.**Without giving up these nine things you can’t realize perfection.*";
P_HTM[1861]="*Nava, bhikkhave, dhamme pahāya bhabbo arahattaṃ sacchikātuṃ.**After giving up nine things you can realize perfection.*";
P_HTM[1862]="*Katame nava?**What nine?*";
P_HTM[1863]="*Rāgaṃ, dosaṃ, mohaṃ, kodhaṃ, upanāhaṃ, makkhaṃ, paḷāsaṃ, issaṃ, macchariyaṃ—**Greed, hate, delusion, anger, hostility, offensiveness, contempt, jealousy, and stinginess.*";
P_HTM[1864]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, nava dhamme pahāya bhabbo arahattaṃ sacchikātun”ti.**After giving up these nine things you can realize the fruit of perfection.”*";
P_HTM[1865]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1866]="*Khemavaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[1867]="*Khemo ca amatañceva,* **";
P_HTM[1868]="*Abhayaṃ passaddhiyena ca;* **";
P_HTM[1869]="*Nirodho anupubbo ca,* **";
P_HTM[1870]="*Dhammaṃ pahāya bhabbena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[1871]="*1(10) 5. Rāgapeyyālaṃ**Mindfulness Meditation*";
P_HTM[1872]="*1. Sikkhādubbalyasuttaṃ**Weaknesses in Training and Mindfulness Meditation*";
P_HTM[1873]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, sikkhādubbalyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five weaknesses when you’re training.*";
P_HTM[1874]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1875]="*Pāṇātipāto, adinnādānaṃ, kāmesumicchācāro, musāvādo, surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhānaṃ—**Killing living creatures, stealing, sexual misconduct, lying, and using alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.*";
P_HTM[1876]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca sikkhādubbalyāni.**These are the five weaknesses when you’re training.*";
P_HTM[1877]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ sikkhādubbalyānaṃ pahānāya cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā.**To give up these five weaknesses in your training you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[1878]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1879]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1880]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[1881]="*citte …**They meditate observing an aspect of the mind …*";
P_HTM[1882]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing an aspect of principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1883]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ sikkhādubbalyānaṃ pahānāya ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**To give up those five weaknesses in your training you should develop these four kinds of mindfulness meditation.”*";
P_HTM[1884]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1885]="*2. Nīvaraṇasuttaṃ**Hindrances*";
P_HTM[1886]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, nīvaraṇāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five hindrances.*";
P_HTM[1887]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1888]="*Kāmacchandanīvaraṇaṃ, byāpādanīvaraṇaṃ, thinamiddhanīvaraṇaṃ, uddhaccakukkuccanīvaraṇaṃ, vicikicchānīvaraṇaṃ—**Sensual desire, ill will, dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, and doubt.*";
P_HTM[1889]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca nīvaraṇāni.**These are the five hindrances.*";
P_HTM[1890]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ nīvaraṇānaṃ pahānāya cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā.**To give up these five hindrances you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[1891]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1892]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1893]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[1894]="*citte …**They meditate observing an aspect of the mind …*";
P_HTM[1895]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing an aspect of principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1896]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ nīvaraṇānaṃ pahānāya ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**To give up those five hindrances you should develop these four kinds of mindfulness meditation.”*";
P_HTM[1897]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1898]="*3. Kāmaguṇasuttaṃ**Kinds of Sensual Stimulation*";
P_HTM[1899]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, kāmaguṇā.**“Mendicants, there are these five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[1900]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1901]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā,**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1902]="*sotaviññeyyā saddā … pe …**Sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[1903]="*ghānaviññeyyā gandhā …**Smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[1904]="*jivhāviññeyyā rasā …**Tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[1905]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1906]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca kāmaguṇā.**These are the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[1907]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ kāmaguṇānaṃ pahānāya … pe … ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**To give up these five kinds of sensual stimulation you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation. …”*";
P_HTM[1908]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1909]="*4. Upādānakkhandhasuttaṃ**Grasping Aggregates*";
P_HTM[1910]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, upādānakkhandhā.**“Mendicants, there are these five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[1911]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1912]="*Rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho—**The grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1913]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, pañcupādānakkhandhā.**These are the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[1914]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ upādānakkhandhānaṃ pahānāya … pe … ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**To give up these five grasping aggregates you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation. …”*";
P_HTM[1915]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1916]="*5. Orambhāgiyasuttaṃ**Lower Fetters*";
P_HTM[1917]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, orambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**“Mendicants, there are five lower fetters.*";
P_HTM[1918]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1919]="*Sakkāyadiṭṭhi, vicikicchā, sīlabbataparāmāso, kāmacchando, byāpādo—**Identity view, doubt, misapprehension of precepts and observances, sensual desire, and ill will.*";
P_HTM[1920]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcorambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**These are the five lower fetters.*";
P_HTM[1921]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ pahānāya … pe … ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**To give up these five lower fetters you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation. …”*";
P_HTM[1922]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1923]="*6. Gatisuttaṃ**Places of Rebirth*";
P_HTM[1924]="*“Pañcimā, bhikkhave, gatiyo.**“Mendicants, there are five destinations.*";
P_HTM[1925]="*Katamā pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1926]="*Nirayo, tiracchānayoni, pettivisayo, manussā, devā—**Hell, the animal realm, the ghost realm, humanity, and the gods.*";
P_HTM[1927]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, pañca gatiyo.**These are the five destinations.*";
P_HTM[1928]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ gatīnaṃ pahānāya … pe … ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**To give up these five destinations you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation. …”*";
P_HTM[1929]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1930]="*7. Macchariyasuttaṃ**Stinginess*";
P_HTM[1931]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, macchariyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five kinds of stinginess.*";
P_HTM[1932]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1933]="*Āvāsamacchariyaṃ, kulamacchariyaṃ, lābhamacchariyaṃ, vaṇṇamacchariyaṃ, dhammamacchariyaṃ—**Stinginess with dwellings, families, material possessions, praise, and the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1934]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca macchariyāni.**These are the five kinds of stinginess.*";
P_HTM[1935]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ macchariyānaṃ pahānāya … pe … ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**To give up these five kinds of stinginess you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation. …”*";
P_HTM[1936]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1937]="*8. Uddhambhāgiyasuttaṃ**Higher Fetters*";
P_HTM[1938]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, uddhambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**“Mendicants, there are five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[1939]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1940]="*Rūparāgo, arūparāgo, māno, uddhaccaṃ, avijjā—**Desire for rebirth in the realm of luminous form, desire for rebirth in the formless realm, conceit, restlessness, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[1941]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcuddhambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**These are the five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[1942]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ uddhambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ pahānāya … pe … ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**To give up these five higher fetters you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation. …”*";
P_HTM[1943]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1944]="*9. Cetokhilasuttaṃ**Emotional Barrenness*";
P_HTM[1945]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, cetokhilā.**“Mendicants, there are five kinds of emotional barrenness.*";
P_HTM[1946]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1947]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satthari kaṅkhati vicikicchati nādhimuccati na sampasīdati.**Firstly, a mendicant has doubts about the Teacher. They’re uncertain, undecided, and lacking confidence.*";
P_HTM[1948]="*Yo so, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satthari kaṅkhati vicikicchati nādhimuccati na sampasīdati, tassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya.**This being so, their mind doesn’t incline toward keenness, commitment, persistence, and striving.*";
P_HTM[1949]="*Yassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya, ayaṃ paṭhamo cetokhilo.**This is the first kind of emotional barrenness.*";
P_HTM[1950]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu dhamme kaṅkhati … pe …**Furthermore, a mendicant has doubts about the teaching …*";
P_HTM[1951]="*saṅghe kaṅkhati …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[1952]="*sikkhāya kaṅkhati …**the training …*";
P_HTM[1953]="*sabrahmacārīsu kupito hoti anattamano āhatacitto khilajāto.**A mendicant is angry and upset with their spiritual companions, resentful and closed off.*";
P_HTM[1954]="*Yo so, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sabrahmacārīsu kupito hoti anattamano āhatacitto khilajāto, tassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya.**This being so, their mind doesn’t incline toward keenness, commitment, persistence, and striving.*";
P_HTM[1955]="*Yassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya, ayaṃ pañcamo cetokhilo.**This is the fifth kind of emotional barrenness.*";
P_HTM[1956]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ cetokhilānaṃ pahānāya … pe … ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**To give up these five kinds of emotional barrenness you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation. …”*";
P_HTM[1957]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1958]="*10. Cetasovinibandhasuttaṃ**Emotional Shackles*";
P_HTM[1959]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, cetasovinibandhā.**“Mendicants, there are these five emotional shackles.*";
P_HTM[1960]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1961]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāmesu avītarāgo hoti avigatacchando avigatapemo avigatapipāso avigatapariḷāho avigatataṇho.**Firstly, a mendicant isn’t free of greed, desire, fondness, thirst, passion, and craving for sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[1962]="*Yo so, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāmesu avītarāgo hoti avigatacchando avigatapemo avigatapipāso avigatapariḷāho avigatataṇho, tassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya.**This being so, their mind doesn’t incline toward keenness, commitment, persistence, and striving.*";
P_HTM[1963]="*Yassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya, ayaṃ paṭhamo cetasovinibandho.**This is the first emotional shackle.*";
P_HTM[1964]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye avītarāgo hoti … pe …**Furthermore, a mendicant isn’t free of greed for the body …*";
P_HTM[1965]="*rūpe avītarāgo hoti …**They’re not free of greed for form …*";
P_HTM[1966]="*yāvadatthaṃ udarāvadehakaṃ bhuñjitvā seyyasukhaṃ passasukhaṃ middhasukhaṃ anuyutto viharati …**They eat as much as they like until their belly is full, then indulge in the pleasures of sleeping, lying, and drowsing …*";
P_HTM[1967]="*aññataraṃ devanikāyaṃ paṇidhāya brahmacariyaṃ carati: ‘imināhaṃ sīlena vā vatena vā tapena vā brahmacariyena vā devo vā bhavissāmi devaññataro vā’ti.**They live the spiritual life wishing to be reborn in one of the orders of gods: ‘By this precept or observance or mortification or spiritual life, may I become one of the gods!’*";
P_HTM[1968]="*Yo so, bhikkhave, bhikkhu aññataraṃ devanikāyaṃ paṇidhāya brahmacariyaṃ carati: ‘imināhaṃ sīlena vā vatena vā tapena vā brahmacariyena vā devo vā bhavissāmi devaññataro vā’ti, tassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya.**This being so, their mind doesn’t incline toward keenness, commitment, persistence, and striving.*";
P_HTM[1969]="*Yassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya, ayaṃ pañcamo cetasovinibandho.**This is the fifth emotional shackle.*";
P_HTM[1970]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca cetasovinibandhā.**These are the five emotional shackles.*";
P_HTM[1971]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ cetasovinibandhānaṃ pahānāya cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā.**To give up these five emotional shackles you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[1972]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1973]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1974]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[1975]="*citte …**They meditate observing an aspect of the mind …*";
P_HTM[1976]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing an aspect of principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1977]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ cetasovinibandhānaṃ pahānāya ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**To give up these five emotional shackles you should develop these four kinds of mindfulness meditation.”*";
P_HTM[1978]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1979]="*Satipaṭṭhānavaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[1980]="*Sikkhā nīvaraṇākāmā,* **";
P_HTM[1981]="*Khandhā ca orambhāgiyā gati;* **";
P_HTM[1982]="*Maccheraṃ uddhambhāgiyā aṭṭhamaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1983]="*Cetokhilā vinibandhāti.* **";
P_HTM[1984]="*1(10) 5. Rāgapeyyālaṃ**Right Efforts*";
P_HTM[1985]="*1. Sikkhasuttaṃ**Weaknesses in Training and Effort*";
P_HTM[1986]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, sikkhādubbalyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five weaknesses when you’re training.*";
P_HTM[1987]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1988]="*Pāṇātipāto … pe … surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhānaṃ—**Killing living creatures, stealing, sexual misconduct, lying, and using alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.*";
P_HTM[1989]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca sikkhādubbalyāni.**These are the five weaknesses when you’re training.*";
P_HTM[1990]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ sikkhādubbalyānaṃ pahānāya cattāro sammappadhānā bhāvetabbā.**To give up these five weaknesses in your training you should develop the four right efforts.*";
P_HTM[1991]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1992]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu anuppannānaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ anuppādāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati;**It’s when a mendicant generates enthusiasm, tries, makes an effort, exerts the mind, and strives so that bad, unskillful qualities don’t arise.*";
P_HTM[1993]="*uppannānaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati;**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that bad, unskillful qualities that have arisen are given up.*";
P_HTM[1994]="*anuppannānaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ uppādāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati;**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that skillful qualities arise.*";
P_HTM[1995]="*uppannānaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ ṭhitiyā asammosāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati.**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that skillful qualities that have arisen remain, are not lost, but increase, mature, and are completed by development.*";
P_HTM[1996]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ sikkhādubbalyānaṃ pahānāya ime cattāro sammappadhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**To give up these five weaknesses in your training you should develop these four right efforts.”*";
P_HTM[1997]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1998]="*10. Cetasovinibandhasuttaṃ**74–81. Nīvaraṇasuttādi*";
P_HTM[1999]="*(Yathā satipaṭṭhānavagge tathā sammappadhānavasena vitthāretabbā.)**(This should be expanded in detail as in the chapter on mindfulness meditation.)*";
P_HTM[2000]="*1(10) 5. Rāgapeyyālaṃ**Right Efforts*";
P_HTM[2001]="*1. Sikkhasuttaṃ**Emotional Shackles*";
P_HTM[2002]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, cetasovinibandhā.**“Mendicants, there are these five emotional shackles.*";
P_HTM[2003]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[2004]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāmesu avītarāgo hoti … pe …**Firstly, a mendicant isn’t free of greed, desire, fondness, thirst, passion, and craving for sensual pleasures. …*";
P_HTM[2005]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca cetasovinibandhā.**These are the five emotional shackles.*";
P_HTM[2006]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ cetasovinibandhānaṃ pahānāya cattāro sammappadhānā bhāvetabbā.**To give up these five emotional shackles you should develop the four right efforts.*";
P_HTM[2007]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2008]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu anuppannānaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ anuppādāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati;**It’s when a mendicant generates enthusiasm, tries, makes an effort, exerts the mind, and strives so that bad, unskillful qualities don’t arise. …*";
P_HTM[2009]="*uppannānaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya …**so that unskillful qualities are given up …*";
P_HTM[2010]="*anuppannānaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ uppādāya …**so that skillful qualities arise …*";
P_HTM[2011]="*uppannānaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ ṭhitiyā asammosāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati.**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that skillful qualities that have arisen remain, are not lost, but increase, mature, and are completed by development.*";
P_HTM[2012]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ cetasovinibandhānaṃ pahānāya ime cattāro sammappadhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**To give up these five emotional shackles you should develop these four right efforts.”*";
P_HTM[2013]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2014]="*Sammappadhānavaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[2015]="*10. Cetasovinibandhasuttaṃ**Weaknesses in Training and the Bases of Psychic Power*";
P_HTM[2016]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, sikkhādubbalyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five weaknesses when you’re training.*";
P_HTM[2017]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[2018]="*Pāṇātipāto … pe … surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhānaṃ—**Killing living creatures, stealing, sexual misconduct, lying, and using alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.*";
P_HTM[2019]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca sikkhādubbalyāni.**These are the five weaknesses when you’re training.*";
P_HTM[2020]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ sikkhādubbalyānaṃ pahānāya cattāro iddhipādā bhāvetabbā.**To give up these five weaknesses in your training you should develop the four bases of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[2021]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2022]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu chandasamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti,**It’s when a mendicant develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to enthusiasm, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[2023]="*vīriyasamādhi …**They develop the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to energy, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[2024]="*cittasamādhi …**They develop the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to mental development, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[2025]="*vīmaṃsāsamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti.**They develop the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to inquiry, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[2026]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ sikkhādubbalyānaṃ pahānāya ime cattāro iddhipādā bhāvetabbā”ti.**To give up these five weaknesses in your training you should develop these four bases of psychic power.”*";
